  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Letter to Yi Ga-geo of Youzhou
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit that even the hives of bees and the burrows of ants teem with corruption, yet fierce warriors have failed to crush the villains—surely this grieves the hearts of every righteous soul and loyal minister.

    I have long believed that though we received the imperial decree last year and turned our forces toward the frontier, if we do not act decisively now, I fear we shall accomplish nothing. Already I have traveled through the Central Lands, reviewing the great armies, waiting for the moment to strike the raiders and march upon the Bian road. Let us set our sights on a hundred victories and determine this one campaign with unwavering resolve—the people united in purpose, our efforts joined in common cause.

    You, Minister and Great Lord, carry the honored lineage of the Zhou clan and hold rank bestowed by the Han court. Surely your heart brims with devotion to the state, and your mind harbors the wisdom to bring peace to the realm. Witnessing these calamities, how could you not grieve and labor with concern?

    Now that I have undertaken this expedition, I come before you with this petition: I humbly beg that you lend us soldiers to aid in subduing the brigands. Grant us five thousand of your finest cavalry, and they shall prove worth a hundred thousand weary troops from other provinces. The capital shall be recovered within mere days. I have already submitted memorials to avoid acting on my own authority, yet while my plea differs from Shen Baoxu's cry for urgent aid, it may be tested like Zhao Chongguo's request to campaign. I pray you will look upon this with clear wisdom and grant your consent. I dare not monopolize the glory—let us share equitably in the rewards. My loyalty burns with sincerity here. I humbly entreat you: sustain this resolve from beginning to end, and soon reveal your answer. Do not disappoint my fervent hopes, which I express with hands clasped in reverence.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Shen Baoxu: A historical figure from ancient China known for his desperate plea to the state of Qin for military assistance during a crisis.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhao Chongguo: A celebrated Han dynasty general whose request to lead a military campaign was ultimately approved, resulting in decisive victory.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Bian road' (汴道) likely refers to a strategic route toward the capital during military campaigns of Choi Chi-won's era.
